I thought of all the possibilities
of what could happen,

4
00:01:29,578 --> 00:01:31,944
and it kept me up at night.

5
00:01:39,521 --> 00:01:42,285
The story that Ric
showed me at the beginning

6
00:01:42,357 --> 00:01:44,587
was just the tip of the iceberg.

7
00:03:01,303 --> 00:03:03,999
Here it is... the town of Taiji.

8
00:03:05,674 --> 00:03:08,040
The little town
with a really big secret.

9
00:03:10,645 --> 00:03:12,772
It's funny driving into Taiji.

10
00:03:12,848 --> 00:03:15,043
It's kind of like <i>The Twilight Zone</i>.

11
00:03:15,117 --> 00:03:16,880
It's so bizarre

12
00:03:16,952 --> 00:03:19,182
because if you didn't know
what's going on over here,

13
00:03:19,254 --> 00:03:22,917
you would think this is a town
that loved dolphins and whales.

14
00:03:22,991 --> 00:03:28,224
On our left here is the infamous
Taiji Whale Museum.

15
00:03:28,296 --> 00:03:30,821
And I really, really
hate this place.

16
00:03:32,334 --> 00:03:34,165
When we first got to Japan,

17
00:03:34,236 --> 00:03:36,261
Ric O'Barry was incredibly frustrated.

18
00:03:36,338 --> 00:03:38,135
He said, "Oh, you have
to wear a mask.

19
00:03:38,206 --> 00:03:39,696
Otherwise, they'll know
that we're here."

20
00:03:39,775 --> 00:03:41,675
And I thought, okay, all right.

21
00:03:41,743 --> 00:03:43,210
There's the police.

22
00:03:43,278 --> 00:03:45,872
I've got to hunch over
and change my shape

23
00:03:45,947 --> 00:03:48,415
so they think
I'm just some old Japanese guy.

24
00:03:50,252 --> 00:03:51,879
I thought, you know, what am I doing?

25
00:03:51,953 --> 00:03:54,547
I went halfway across the world
to end up in this car,

26
00:03:54,623 --> 00:03:56,352
locked up with this paranoid guy.

27
00:03:56,424 --> 00:03:57,516
Somebody's behind me.

28
00:03:57,592 --> 00:03:59,822
I don't know who that is.

29
00:03:59,895 --> 00:04:01,658
Yep. He's coming. He's coming.

30
00:04:01,730 --> 00:04:02,754
Is he really?

31
00:04:02,831 --> 00:04:05,163
Yeah. I've been doing this too long.

32
00:04:05,233 --> 00:04:08,327
The mayor of this town
actually gave me the key to the city.

33
00:04:08,403 --> 00:04:09,927
I was welcome then.

34
00:04:10,005 --> 00:04:12,303
Today they'd kill me if they could.

35
00:04:12,374 --> 00:04:13,898
And I'm not exaggerating.

36
00:04:13,975 --> 00:04:16,443
If these fishermen could
catch me and kill me,

37
00:04:16,511 --> 00:04:18,035
they would.

38
00:04:19,347 --> 00:04:21,008
About three years ago,

39
00:04:21,082 --> 00:04:23,346
my friend Jim Clark and I
started this organization...

40
00:04:23,418 --> 00:04:26,717
The Oceanic Preservation Society, OPS.

41
00:04:26,788 --> 00:04:29,723
We've been diving for over 35 years,

42
00:04:29,791 --> 00:04:32,817
and you could go back to the same
dive spot year after year

43
00:04:32,894 --> 00:04:34,486
and literally see
the degradation of the oceans

44
00:04:34,563 --> 00:04:36,292
before your very eyes.

45
00:04:36,364 --> 00:04:39,458
There's major extinctions
going on right now in our lifetime.

46
00:04:41,002 --> 00:04:42,230
Jim had the idea

47
00:04:42,304 --> 00:04:44,932
to try to do something
about it, to stop this,

48
00:04:45,006 --> 00:04:47,736
so I began documenting
reefs around the world.

49
00:04:47,809 --> 00:04:51,074
I went to a marine mammal conference
down in San Diego.

50
00:04:51,613 --> 00:04:54,946
There was 2,000 of the world's
top marine mammal scientists,

51
00:04:55,016 --> 00:04:58,452
and Ric O'Barry was supposed
to be the keynote speaker,

52
00:04:58,520 --> 00:04:59,851
and at the last minute,

53
00:04:59,921 --> 00:05:03,049
the sponsor of the program
pulled him from the ticket.

54
00:05:03,124 --> 00:05:04,591
I thought, oh God, that's interesting.

55
00:05:04,659 --> 00:05:05,853
Well, who's the sponsor?

56
00:05:05,927 --> 00:05:08,020
They said, "Sea World."

57
00:05:22,344 --> 00:05:24,778
A lot of marine mammal
scientists get their money

58
00:05:24,846 --> 00:05:27,440
from Hub Research Institute,

59
00:05:27,515 --> 00:05:30,848
which is the nonprofit arm of Sea World.

60
00:05:32,420 --> 00:05:34,615
They don't like me.

61
00:05:34,689 --> 00:05:37,658
They don't like my message
about captivity,

62
00:05:37,726 --> 00:05:39,318
and they took me off the list.

63
00:05:39,394 --> 00:05:43,455
They wouldn't let me
talk about this dolphin slaughter in Taiji.

64
00:05:43,531 --> 00:05:45,829
I said, "Dolphin slaughter?
What's... What's that about?"

65
00:05:45,901 --> 00:05:48,392
He says, "Well, I'm going next week.

66
00:05:48,470 --> 00:05:49,596
You want to come?"

67
00:05:52,807 --> 00:05:57,141
Now we're approaching the area
that's most important.

68
00:05:59,014 --> 00:06:01,346
That's a dolphin's
worst nightmare right there.

69
00:06:02,984 --> 00:06:06,147
Hundreds of thousands
of dolphins have died there.

70
00:06:06,221 --> 00:06:10,089
You'll see the signs...
"Keep Out," "Danger."

71
00:06:10,158 --> 00:06:13,821
There are fishermen walking
around these hills with knives.

72
00:06:13,895 --> 00:06:16,295
This is a national park.

73
00:06:16,364 --> 00:06:17,763
The fishermen told me.

74
00:06:17,832 --> 00:06:21,461
They said, "If the world finds out
what goes on here,

75
00:06:21,536 --> 00:06:23,470
we'll be shut down."

76
00:06:23,538 --> 00:06:24,971
Can you imagine that?

77
00:06:25,040 --> 00:06:26,803
They actually told us that.

78
00:06:26,875 --> 00:06:30,367
We knew to get in there
and film exactly what happens.

79
00:06:30,445 --> 00:06:32,208
We need to know the truth.

80
00:06:35,317 --> 00:06:37,148
When we got back to the hotel...

81
00:06:37,218 --> 00:06:39,015
It's a big spa hotel,

82
00:06:39,087 --> 00:06:41,317
people going by in robes,

83
00:06:41,389 --> 00:06:45,325
and there's these three
undercover cops talking to Ric.

84
00:06:53,768 --> 00:06:54,792
No.

85
00:06:58,306 --> 00:06:59,364
No.

86
00:07:00,442 --> 00:07:01,431
- No.
- No?

87
00:07:01,509 --> 00:07:03,170
No.

88
00:07:03,244 --> 00:07:04,370
In the background,

89
00:07:04,446 --> 00:07:07,677
you could see these dolphin boats
going by in the window,

90
00:07:07,749 --> 00:07:09,580
and it was just... it was so surreal.

91
00:07:09,651 --> 00:07:11,585
I couldn't... I wanted to laugh,

92
00:07:11,653 --> 00:07:13,518
and I wanted to scream
at the same time.

93
00:07:19,794 --> 00:07:21,421
No. No.

94
00:07:22,597 --> 00:07:23,586
Right. I know.

95
00:07:25,166 --> 00:07:26,155
Yeah.

96
00:07:26,234 --> 00:07:27,929
I don't enter. No, no.

97
00:07:29,004 --> 00:07:30,471
Thank you so much, and...

98
00:07:30,538 --> 00:07:31,527
You're welcome.

99
00:07:31,606 --> 00:07:33,471
- See you again.
- Okay. Bye-bye.

100
00:07:33,541 --> 00:07:36,772
I never planned
on being an activist.

101
00:07:36,845 --> 00:07:38,574
One thing leads to another,

102
00:07:38,646 --> 00:07:41,740
and now if there's
a dolphin in trouble

103
00:07:41,816 --> 00:07:43,579
anywhere in the world,

104
00:07:43,651 --> 00:07:44,879
my phone will ring.

105
00:07:47,122 --> 00:07:51,456
Ric is world famous
for his work with dolphins.

106
00:07:51,526 --> 00:07:55,257
The first time I connected
with him in recent years

107
00:07:55,330 --> 00:07:57,423
was on a trip down to Nicaragua.

108
00:07:58,533 --> 00:07:59,830
There were two dolphins

109
00:07:59,901 --> 00:08:02,199
in a swimming pool filled
with their own excrement.

110
00:08:02,270 --> 00:08:06,707
Ric somehow enlisted
the military forces of Nicaragua.

111
00:08:06,775 --> 00:08:09,335
The dolphins were
put on a helicopter,

112
00:08:09,411 --> 00:08:11,038
and then out to sea we go,

113
00:08:11,112 --> 00:08:12,670
and the dolphins are released.

114
00:08:14,682 --> 00:08:17,412
We're going to capture these dolphins
out of the wild

115
00:08:17,485 --> 00:08:18,850
and bring them into captivity.

116
00:08:18,920 --> 00:08:21,980
There are people
who will set them free.

117
00:08:23,858 --> 00:08:25,519
In March of this year,

118
00:08:25,593 --> 00:08:28,221
O'Barry was arrested
three times in Florida

119
00:08:28,296 --> 00:08:31,026
for trying to free some captive dolphins.

120
00:08:31,099 --> 00:08:33,727
On Earth Day, he was
arrested for the same thing

121
00:08:33,802 --> 00:08:35,929
on the Island of Bimini.

122
00:08:36,004 --> 00:08:37,767
How many times
have you been arrested?

123
00:08:37,839 --> 00:08:40,103
This year?

124
00:08:41,342 --> 00:08:45,039
Swimmer, you're within
a government-authorized test area.

125
00:08:45,113 --> 00:08:47,172
You are holding up
a government project.

126
00:08:47,248 --> 00:08:49,113
Do you understand?

127
00:08:49,184 --> 00:08:50,845
God damn it.

128
00:08:53,188 --> 00:08:56,817
A dolphin in the right spot
can make a million dollars a year.

129
00:08:56,891 --> 00:08:58,950
There's a lot of money in it.

130
00:08:59,027 --> 00:09:00,289
If you get in their way...

131
00:09:00,361 --> 00:09:01,658
and I get in their way...

132
00:09:01,729 --> 00:09:04,095
it can be very, very dangerous.

133
00:09:05,800 --> 00:09:07,597
Jane Tipson, she was murdered.

134
00:09:07,669 --> 00:09:11,070
She's the second colleague
I've worked with that was murdered.

135
00:09:11,139 --> 00:09:12,663
The other one was Jenny May.

136
00:09:12,740 --> 00:09:16,972
We were trying to stop
the traffic in Russian dolphins,

137
00:09:17,045 --> 00:09:18,774
and it involved a hunger strike.

138
00:09:18,847 --> 00:09:21,247
About the tenth day, I passed out,

139
00:09:21,316 --> 00:09:22,874
and I went to a hospital there,

140
00:09:22,951 --> 00:09:24,248
so Jenny became a target,

141
00:09:24,319 --> 00:09:26,082
and they followed her
down the beach

142
00:09:26,154 --> 00:09:28,315
and strangled her with her own belt.

143
00:09:30,158 --> 00:09:33,525
These dolphins are symbolic
of a new day for the environment.

144
00:09:33,595 --> 00:09:36,564
It's all about respect now,
not exploitation.

145
00:09:39,934 --> 00:09:41,834
I feel somewhat responsible

146
00:09:41,903 --> 00:09:44,337
because it was the <i>Flipper</i> TV series

147
00:09:44,405 --> 00:09:48,034
that created this
multi-billion-dollar industry.

148
00:09:48,109 --> 00:09:52,478
It created this desire
to swim with them and kiss them

149
00:09:52,547 --> 00:09:55,175
and hold them and hug them
and love them to death,

150
00:09:55,250 --> 00:09:57,377
and it created all these captures.

151
00:10:10,999 --> 00:10:12,864
There were five female dolphins

152
00:10:12,934 --> 00:10:15,164
who collectively played
the part of Flipper.

153
00:10:15,236 --> 00:10:17,534
I captured the five dolphins myself.

154
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:22,898
The entire crew turns to
with battle station teamwork.

155
00:10:22,977 --> 00:10:24,535
When the porpoise is sighted,

156
00:10:24,612 --> 00:10:26,671
not a moment can be lost.

157
00:10:26,748 --> 00:10:29,148
The men handle this creature
with infinite care.

158
00:10:29,217 --> 00:10:33,153
She seems to sense
that she has come home,

159
00:10:33,221 --> 00:10:35,917
that no harm will come to her now.

160
00:10:35,990 --> 00:10:38,049
She is safe.

161
00:10:46,601 --> 00:10:50,093
When I started training dolphins,
there was no manual.

162
00:10:50,171 --> 00:10:51,433
I would get the script,

163
00:10:51,506 --> 00:10:55,033
and it says "Flipper goes over
to the dock "and picks up the gun

164
00:10:55,109 --> 00:10:57,202
and then swims down left to right."

165
00:10:57,278 --> 00:10:59,872
I had to actually translate that
into action somehow.

166
00:10:59,948 --> 00:11:01,176
Thanks, Flipper.

167
00:11:02,584 --> 00:11:04,518
Yeah. Thanks, Flipper.

168
00:11:06,454 --> 00:11:08,547
The thing that really struck me

169
00:11:08,623 --> 00:11:11,251
was that they're smarter
than we think they are.

170
00:11:13,595 --> 00:11:15,927
The house that you see
on the <i>Flipper</i> set

171
00:11:15,997 --> 00:11:17,123
where the family lives

172
00:11:17,198 --> 00:11:18,426
was actually my house.

173
00:11:18,499 --> 00:11:21,627
I lived there all year round
for seven years.

174
00:11:21,703 --> 00:11:23,227
And right in front of the house

175
00:11:23,304 --> 00:11:25,431
there was a lake, salt water lake,

176
00:11:25,506 --> 00:11:28,532
and that's where Flipper was
at the end of the dock.

177
00:11:28,610 --> 00:11:32,444
When <i>Flipper</i> came on television
at Friday night at 7:30,

178
00:11:32,513 --> 00:11:34,606
I would take my television
set from the house

179
00:11:34,682 --> 00:11:36,013
and go down the end of the dock

180
00:11:36,084 --> 00:11:37,574
with a long extension cord,

181
00:11:37,652 --> 00:11:41,110
and Cathy would watch
herself on television,

182
00:11:41,189 --> 00:11:44,784
and she could tell the difference
between herself and Suzy,

183
00:11:44,859 --> 00:11:47,293
who was another Flipper
dolphin that was used.

184
00:11:48,730 --> 00:11:51,893
I knew then they were self-aware,

185
00:11:51,966 --> 00:11:56,266
and when you become conscious
of this nonhuman intelligence,

186
00:11:56,337 --> 00:11:59,568
you realize after a while
they don't really belong in captivity.

187
00:11:59,641 --> 00:12:02,633
But I didn't do anything about it.

188
00:12:04,178 --> 00:12:07,045
One day, it all ended.

189
00:12:07,115 --> 00:12:10,778
Like the props, they went
back to the Miami Seaquarium.

190
00:12:18,393 --> 00:12:21,920
When you just walk into this place
and the music is playing,

191
00:12:21,996 --> 00:12:24,362
the dolphin is jumping and smiling,

192
00:12:24,432 --> 00:12:27,026
it's hard to see the problem.

193
00:12:27,101 --> 00:12:32,129
But a dolphin's smile
is nature's greatest deception.

194
00:12:32,206 --> 00:12:36,165
It creates the illusion
they're always happy.

195
00:12:50,391 --> 00:12:54,191
The nerve center of any dolphinarium
is the fish house.

196
00:12:54,262 --> 00:12:56,856
And if you go to any one
of these fish houses,

197
00:12:56,931 --> 00:13:00,367
you'll see bottles
of Maalox and Tagamet.

198
00:13:00,435 --> 00:13:03,336
And they're used
because dolphins get ulcers,

199
00:13:03,404 --> 00:13:05,497
because they're all stressed out.

200
00:13:07,375 --> 00:13:09,570
You have to see them in the wild

201
00:13:09,644 --> 00:13:12,374
to understand
why captivity doesn't work.

202
00:13:27,362 --> 00:13:31,731
In the wild, they're traveling
40 miles a day.

203
00:13:31,799 --> 00:13:35,132
They could be surfing
in one area in the morning,

204
00:13:35,203 --> 00:13:38,604
and the next hour
they could be 25 miles away

205
00:13:38,673 --> 00:13:41,540
feeding or socializing.

206
00:13:42,677 --> 00:13:46,841
Dolphins are acoustic creatures.

207
00:13:46,914 --> 00:13:48,745
That's their primary sense.

208
00:13:51,018 --> 00:13:53,680
The best sonar that man has

209
00:13:53,755 --> 00:13:56,349
is a toy compared
to the dolphins' sonar.

210
00:13:56,424 --> 00:13:57,652
When you're in the water,

211
00:13:57,725 --> 00:13:59,420
the dolphins can see
right through you.

212
00:13:59,494 --> 00:14:01,962
They can see your heart beating.

213
00:14:02,029 --> 00:14:03,428
They can see your bones.

214
00:14:03,498 --> 00:14:04,829
They can see if you're pregnant.

215
00:14:06,234 --> 00:14:10,796
They get a lot of information
with their sound.

216
00:14:11,339 --> 00:14:14,206
The dolphin is captured
and put in a concrete tank

217
00:14:14,275 --> 00:14:18,507
surrounded by a stadium
full of screaming people.

218
00:14:21,816 --> 00:14:24,683
At the National Aquarium in Baltimore,

219
00:14:24,752 --> 00:14:27,482
when it first opened,
dolphins were dying left and right.

220
00:14:27,555 --> 00:14:28,852
They couldn't keep dolphins alive,

221
00:14:28,923 --> 00:14:30,288
and they finally figured out

222
00:14:30,358 --> 00:14:35,295
it's because the filtration system
was making a lot of noise.

223
00:14:36,697 --> 00:14:39,257
It's the stress that kills them.

224
00:14:40,768 --> 00:14:43,100
So they're very sensitive to sound.

225
00:14:43,171 --> 00:14:45,162
That's their primary sense,

226
00:14:45,239 --> 00:14:48,902
and that's their downfall in Taiji.

227
00:14:55,082 --> 00:14:57,175
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7...

228
00:14:57,251 --> 00:14:58,479
There's 12 of them.

229
00:14:58,553 --> 00:15:00,680
This is a classic drive,

230
00:15:00,755 --> 00:15:02,347
what you're watching here.

231
00:15:03,558 --> 00:15:04,991
There are migratory routes

232
00:15:05,059 --> 00:15:07,892
that dolphins have been using
for thousands of years,

233
00:15:07,962 --> 00:15:10,760
and they just wait
till the dolphins come by.

234
00:15:10,832 --> 00:15:13,699
The boats then put these
long poles in the water

235
00:15:13,768 --> 00:15:16,828
which have a flange on the bottom,

236
00:15:16,904 --> 00:15:20,431
and they just bang on these poles
with hammers,

237
00:15:20,508 --> 00:15:25,810
and they create a wall of sound
which frightens the dolphins.

238
00:15:28,015 --> 00:15:31,280
There were several hundred dolphins
being driven ashore.

239
00:15:31,352 --> 00:15:33,820
I'd never seen so many
dolphins before,

240
00:15:33,888 --> 00:15:36,516
and they were all
running for their lives,

241
00:15:36,591 --> 00:15:38,388
running from this wall of sound.

242
00:15:40,528 --> 00:15:43,964
I think I can actually
hear the banging,

243
00:15:44,031 --> 00:15:45,498
but I hear it all the time.

244
00:15:45,566 --> 00:15:47,124
I hear it in my sleep.

245
00:15:47,201 --> 00:15:50,034
That sound never goes away
once you hear it.

246
00:15:51,539 --> 00:15:53,268
By the time they get to the lagoon,

247
00:15:53,341 --> 00:15:56,674
they're totally freaked out,
stressed out to the max.

248
00:15:56,744 --> 00:15:59,110
They seal it, then they go home.

249
00:16:00,581 --> 00:16:01,809
The next morning,

250
00:16:01,883 --> 00:16:04,545
all of these dolphin trainers
will be lined up

251
00:16:04,619 --> 00:16:09,249
selecting the ones that they want
for the dolphinariums.

252
00:16:24,472 --> 00:16:27,100
They're looking for bottlenose
dolphin, primarily.

253
00:16:27,174 --> 00:16:28,698
They're looking for Flipper,

